{
  "How many protons are in an atom of carbon-12?": "",
  "6": "",
  "14": "",
  "12": "",
  "8": "",
  "Carbon has an atomic number of 6, meaning every carbon atom has exactly 6 protons in its nucleus regardless of the isotope.": "",
  "Which subatomic particle has a negative charge?": "",
  "Proton": "",
  "Positron": "",
  "Electron": "",
  "Neutron": "",
  "Electrons carry a charge of -1 and orbit the nucleus. Protons carry a +1 charge, and neutrons are electrically neutral.": "",
  "Where are protons and neutrons located within an atom?": "",
  "In the electron cloud": "",
  "In the nucleus": "",
  "Between orbitals": "",
  "In the outermost energy level": "",
  "Protons and neutrons reside in the dense, central nucleus of an atom, which contains nearly all of the atom's mass.": "",
  "What is the approximate mass of a proton in atomic mass units (amu)?": "",
  "0 amu": "",
  "1/1836 amu": "",
  "1 amu": "",
  "2 amu": "",
  "A proton has a mass of approximately 1 amu (1.673 x 10^-24 g). Neutrons also have a mass of about 1 amu, while electrons are roughly 1/1836 amu.": "",
  "How many neutrons are in an atom of nitrogen-15?": "",
  "7": "",
  "15": "",
  "22": "",
  "Nitrogen has an atomic number of 7, so it has 7 protons. Neutrons = mass number - atomic number = 15 - 7 = 8 neutrons.": "",
  "What determines the identity of an element?": "",
  "The number of electrons": "",
  "The number of protons": "",
  "The number of neutrons": "",
  "The atomic mass": "",
  "The number of protons (atomic number Z) uniquely defines an element. Changing the number of protons changes the element entirely.": "",
  "A neutral atom of fluorine (Z = 9) has how many electrons?": "",
  "10": "",
  "9": "",
  "19": "",
  "In a neutral atom, the number of electrons equals the number of protons. Since fluorine has 9 protons, a neutral fluorine atom has 9 electrons.": "",
  "Which particle contributes most to the mass of an atom but does not affect its charge?": "",
  "Photon": "",
  "Neutrons have a mass of about 1 amu (similar to protons) but carry no charge, so they contribute significantly to mass without affecting charge.": "",
  "What is the mass number (A) of an atom with 17 protons and 18 neutrons?": "",
  "35": "",
  "18": "",
  "17": "",
  "1": "",
  "Mass number (A) is the sum of protons and neutrons in the nucleus. A = 17 + 18 = 35. This atom is chlorine-35.": "",
  "Which of the following pairs are isotopes of each other?": "",
  "Carbon-12 and Nitrogen-14": "",
  "Sodium-23 and Magnesium-24": "",
  "Oxygen-16 and Oxygen-18": "",
  "Hydrogen-1 and Helium-4": "",
  "Isotopes are atoms of the same element with different numbers of neutrons. Oxygen-16 and Oxygen-18 are both oxygen (Z = 8) but differ in their neutron count.": "",
  "What is the atomic number (Z)?": "",
  "The weighted average mass of all naturally occurring isotopes": "",
  "The number of protons in an atom's nucleus that uniquely identifies the element": "",
  "The total number of protons and neutrons in the nucleus": "",
  "The number of electron shells in an atom": "",
  "The atomic number (Z) is the number of protons in the nucleus. It uniquely identifies each element and determines its position on the periodic table.": "",
  "What does the term 'isotope' mean?": "",
  "Atoms of the same element with different numbers of neutrons": "",
  "Molecules made of two or more different elements": "",
  "Atoms of different elements with the same mass number": "",
  "Ions with different charges from the same element": "",
  "Isotopes are atoms of the same element (same number of protons) that have different numbers of neutrons, giving them different mass numbers.": "",
  "What is the mass number (A) of an atom?": "",
  "The weighted average atomic mass from the periodic table": "",
  "The total number of protons plus neutrons in the nucleus": "",
  "The number of energy levels occupied by electrons": "",
  "The number of electrons orbiting the nucleus": "",
  "The mass number (A) equals the sum of protons (Z) and neutrons (N) in the nucleus, expressed as A = Z + N.": "",
  "What is an ion?": "",
  "A neutral atom with equal numbers of protons and neutrons": "",
  "A molecule composed of two atoms of the same element": "",
  "An atom that has gained or lost electrons, resulting in a net electrical charge": "",
  "An atom with an unstable nucleus that undergoes radioactive decay": "",
  "An ion is an atom that has gained or lost electrons. Cations are positively charged (lost electrons), and anions are negatively charged (gained electrons).": "",
  "What does 'atomic mass unit (amu)' mean?": "",
  "The mass of one mole of atoms of an element": "",
  "The total mass of all neutrons in an atom": "",
  "The mass of a single electron": "",
  "A unit defined as exactly 1/12 the mass of a carbon-12 atom": "",
  "One atomic mass unit (amu) is defined as exactly 1/12 the mass of a carbon-12 atom, which equals approximately 1.661 x 10^-24 grams.": "",
  "What is a cation?": "",
  "A neutral atom with no net charge": "",
  "An atom that has lost one or more electrons, giving it a positive charge": "",
  "An atom that has gained one or more electrons": "",
  "An isotope with more neutrons than protons": "",
  "A cation is a positively charged ion formed when an atom loses one or more electrons. Metals commonly form cations (e.g., Na+ loses one electron).": "",
  "What does 'average atomic mass' mean?": "",
  "The mass number of the lightest isotope": "",
  "The mass of the most abundant isotope of an element": "",
  "The weighted average of the masses of all naturally occurring isotopes of an element based on their relative abundances": "",
  "The simple arithmetic mean of all isotope masses": "",
  "Average atomic mass is the weighted average of the masses of all naturally occurring isotopes, where each isotope's mass is multiplied by its fractional abundance.": "",
  "What is an anion?": "",
  "An atom that has lost electrons and carries a positive charge": "",
  "An atom that has gained one or more electrons, giving it a negative charge": "",
  "An atom with no neutrons": "",
  "A subatomic particle found in the nucleus": "",
  "An anion is a negatively charged ion formed when an atom gains one or more electrons. Nonmetals commonly form anions (e.g., Cl- gains one electron).": "",
  "What does 'nuclear charge' refer to?": "",
  "The net charge of an ion after electron loss or gain": "",
  "The charge contributed by neutrons in the nucleus": "",
  "The total positive charge of the nucleus, equal to the number of protons times the elementary charge": "",
  "The total negative charge from all electrons in an atom": "",
  "Nuclear charge is the total positive charge in the nucleus, determined solely by the number of protons. It attracts electrons and influences atomic properties.": "",
  "What is the 'electron cloud'?": "",
  "The outermost shell of electrons only": "",
  "A region of space around the nucleus where electrons are most likely to be found": "",
  "A cloud of neutrons surrounding the protons": "",
  "The dense central region of the atom containing protons": "",
  "The electron cloud is the region of space around the nucleus where there is a high probability of finding electrons. It represents the volume that electrons occupy in their orbitals.": "",
  "A forensic scientist uses mass spectrometry to analyze a sample found at a crime scene. The instrument separates ions based on their mass-to-charge ratio and identifies the presence of lead isotopes Pb-206 and Pb-208. What property allows the mass spectrometer to distinguish between these two isotopes?": "",
  "They have different numbers of protons": "",
  "They have different numbers of electrons": "",
  "They have different numbers of neutrons, giving them different masses": "",
  "They have different nuclear charges": "",
  "Isotopes of the same element have the same number of protons but different numbers of neutrons. Pb-206 has 124 neutrons and Pb-208 has 126 neutrons, giving them different masses that the mass spectrometer can distinguish.": "",
  "An archaeologist sends a wooden artifact to a lab for radiocarbon dating. The lab measures the ratio of carbon-14 to carbon-12 in the sample. Why is carbon-14 useful for dating while carbon-12 is not?": "",
  "Carbon-12 has fewer protons than carbon-14": "",
  "Carbon-12 is not found in organic materials": "",
  "Carbon-14 is radioactive and decays at a known rate, while carbon-12 is stable": "",
  "Carbon-14 has more protons than carbon-12, making it heavier": "",
  "Carbon-14 is a radioactive isotope that decays with a half-life of about 5,730 years. By comparing the C-14/C-12 ratio in a sample to that in the atmosphere, scientists can estimate the age of organic materials.": "",
  "A patient undergoes a PET scan using fluorine-18 as a radioactive tracer. The F-18 isotope has 9 protons and 9 neutrons. How does F-18 differ from the most common fluorine isotope, F-19?": "",
  "F-18 has one fewer neutron than F-19": "",
  "F-18 has one fewer proton than F-19": "",
  "F-18 has a different atomic number than F-19": "",
  "F-18 has one more electron than F-19": "",
  "Both F-18 and F-19 have 9 protons (same atomic number, same element). F-18 has 9 neutrons while F-19 has 10 neutrons, so F-18 has one fewer neutron.": "",
  "A chemistry student measures the atomic mass of chlorine on the periodic table as 35.45 amu, but knows that individual chlorine atoms have mass numbers of either 35 or 37. Why is the listed atomic mass not a whole number?": "",
  "The periodic table rounds atomic masses to the nearest tenth": "",
  "The value is a weighted average of the masses of Cl-35 and Cl-37 based on their natural abundances": "",
  "Chlorine atoms can have fractional numbers of neutrons": "",
  "The mass includes the mass of the electrons, which adds a decimal portion": "",
  "The atomic mass on the periodic table is a weighted average of all naturally occurring isotopes. Cl-35 (75.77%) and Cl-37 (24.23%) average to approximately 35.45 amu.": "",
  "In a semiconductor fabrication plant, silicon wafers must be extremely pure. Engineers use mass spectrometry to verify that the silicon contains the correct isotopic composition: Si-28 (92.2%), Si-29 (4.7%), and Si-30 (3.1%). If a sample shows an unusually high proportion of Si-30, what would happen to the measured average atomic mass?": "",
  "It would remain unchanged because all isotopes are still silicon": "",
  "It would fluctuate unpredictably": "",
  "It would increase because the heavier isotope is overrepresented in the weighted average": "",
  "It would decrease because Si-30 is lighter": "",
  "Since average atomic mass is a weighted average, increasing the proportion of the heavier isotope (Si-30) shifts the average upward. More Si-30 means more mass contributing to the average.": "",
  "A water treatment facility tests its supply and finds trace amounts of ions. The report states the presence of Ca2+ ions. A technician notes that neutral calcium atoms have 20 electrons. How many electrons does a Ca2+ ion have?": "",
  "20": "",
  "2": "",
  "A Ca2+ ion has lost 2 electrons from the neutral atom. Since neutral calcium has 20 electrons, Ca2+ has 20 - 2 = 18 electrons, giving it a net +2 charge.": "",
  "A nuclear medicine technician prepares a dose of iodine-131 for a thyroid cancer patient. The prescription requires a specific number of atoms. The technician knows that I-131 has 53 protons. How many neutrons does each I-131 atom contain?": "",
  "78": "",
  "131": "",
  "184": "",
  "53": "",
  "Neutrons = mass number - atomic number = 131 - 53 = 78 neutrons. The mass number includes both protons and neutrons in the nucleus.": "",
  "A geochemist analyzing moon rocks finds that the ratio of rubidium-87 to strontium-87 can be used to date the samples. Both have a mass number of 87 but are different elements. What fundamental difference explains why Rb-87 and Sr-87 are different elements despite having the same mass number?": "",
  "They have different atomic masses but the same atomic number": "",
  "They have different numbers of neutrons only": "",
  "The identity of an element is determined by its number of protons (atomic number). Rb has 37 protons and Sr has 38 protons, making them different elements even though they share the same mass number of 87.": "",
  "A student dissolving table salt (NaCl) in water learns that the compound dissociates into Na+ and Cl- ions. The student wonders why sodium forms a +1 ion while chlorine forms a -1 ion. Which explanation correctly relates this to subatomic particles?": "",
  "Sodium loses a neutron to become positive, and chlorine gains a neutron to become negative": "",
  "Both atoms share electrons equally, producing partial charges": "",
  "Sodium loses one electron to become Na+ and chlorine gains one electron to become Cl-": "",
  "Sodium gains a proton to become positive, and chlorine loses a proton to become negative": "",
  "Ion formation involves the transfer of electrons. Sodium loses one electron (11 protons, 10 electrons = +1 charge) and chlorine gains one electron (17 protons, 18 electrons = -1 charge).": "",
  "Scientists at CERN use particle accelerators to study fundamental particles. When gold atoms (Au, Z = 79) are stripped of all their electrons and accelerated, they become Au79+ ions. How does the total number of subatomic particles in a Au-197 ion compare to the original neutral atom?": "",
  "The ion has 118 fewer subatomic particles because neutrons and electrons were removed": "",
  "The ion has the same number of subatomic particles because only charge changed": "",
  "The ion has 79 fewer subatomic particles because all electrons were removed": "",
  "The ion has 79 fewer subatomic particles because all protons were removed": "",
  "Stripping all electrons from a gold atom removes 79 electrons (since Z = 79). The nucleus with 79 protons and 118 neutrons remains unchanged. The total count drops by 79 subatomic particles.": ""
